3. Celebration of Easter : the third point of difference, though not actually mentioned here, may, notwithstanding, be the real implication of the reference to Jews <cum ludaeis). WVhen the fourteenth day of the vernal moon fell upon a Sunday, the Roman and Eastern Churches celebrated Easter upon the following Sunday, in order to avoid holding the feast on the same day as the Jews: the Celts‚ however, following a more ancient usage, observed their Easter even on the fourteenth moon, provided it were the Sunday‚ and so appeared to act “with the Jews’⁷ (Beda, H.E., ii, 2 ; v, 21). One inconvenient result, in practical life, of this difference, is pointed out by Beda; that is to say, two neighbouring churches might be engaged at the same time, the one in the glad joyous services of Eastertide‚ the other in the severe exercise of Lenten fasts.
